From our inbox:
Hey, lgbt peeps! Sam here. Just wanted to tell everybody who is having a hard time coming out that there are always going to be people who care about you. Whether that's family, friends, or even random strangers online, people will care. 

I know how hard it is to come out. I was the same way coming out as a bisexual, but once you get used to telling people who you really are, you start to not care as much about what the haters think.

Myself, I suffer from depression and anxiety. I thought years ago that coming out was the hardest thing I could do in life, but now it's a piece of cake. Living with a religious family didn't help either, at the time, but my grandmother has even told me that despite the fact that she doesn't necessarily agree with the gay life, she still loves me. And I even used to have a long distance relationship with a girl who my grandmother turned out to like.

Sorry that this is long, but I just wanted to let everybody know that somewhere out there, even if you don't realize it, you have a friend.
Results from today's poll, rating your coming out experience:

Dear Mr R"
"Even though you're gay, I will always treat you the same way as I do now. I still think about you the same way as I used to. You're a great teacher and these are just some of the word's (sic) that I would describe you as: great, amazing, fantastic, brilliant, awesome and brave.
"The reason why I say brave is because you shared a personal secret which was very brave.
"You don't have to feel scared because I know that everone in the class feels the same way as I do.
"From A x x
PS. We are all proud of you"

I was at Walgreens buying my brother a birthday card. An elderly woman was also in the aisle. She said "can you believe they have wedding cards for two men and look even two women!"

[screams internally]

But she then said "I've seen so many changes in my 80 years, it's wonderful how things are moving forward."

[internal tears of joy]

She then mentioned that she didn't know any gay people but that everyone should be treated like they would want to be treated. I smiled and said "you know one now" and pointed at myself. She smiled, patted my shoulder and said "now I do".

Handsome Desi del Valle stars as a twenty-something Latina lesbian looking for love in this charming indie feature from writer-directorMary Guzman.
Desi's best pal J.T. (Yesenia Aguirre) has three passions: her skateboard, comedienneMarga Gomez, and her friend Desi (not necessarily in that order). When Desi's girlfriend dumps her for a younger woman, J.T. and Desi's other pals try to help her get back into the dating scene. This touching, realistic comedy showcases the familiar sights and sounds of San Francisco's Latino and queer cultures along the way.
This charming first feature from Mary Guzmán is an enjoyable and upbeat look at relationships, from friendly to familial — and everything in between. A fun, intelligent, and sometimes painfully true to life story, we get to tag along the emotional roller coaster of the lesbian dating world.
"A snappy, colorful, and very funny portrait of San Francisco dyke life." – The Advocate
"A humorous look at the dating game on the lesbian scene...a well-written, well-executed film that certainly hits the mark in giving voice to Latina lesbians." – Curve Magazine

I would love for you to share my family photo; we are the Siegrist family. My name is Jesse (in yellow) and my wife is Terry.

My wife and I met in middle school and reconnected in our 20s. At that point we each had a biological child and became a family of four.

With Florida lifting the ban for gays to adopt, back in October 2010 we pursued adoption and our family has grown (as you can see). 

We have known each other over 20 years, have been together 11 years and married 4 years come July. 

She is my rock, my soul, my heart, and my everything; we have overcome many challenges in life, and I look forward to the rest of my life with my wife and kids

About a month ago, our families traveled about 2 hours to Illinois where I could legally marry the love of my life. I've known Carrie since 7th grade when we became good friends. We moved, but stayed in contact throughout the years and saw each other when we could (her baby shower in 2002, when we were both back in town, hard times when we needed a good friend.) About two years ago, we met up again at our hometown festival and have been inseparable since. We've been through alot; a divorce, my coming out to family and friends, being diagnosed with a lifelong illness. Through these struggles, I found exactly what I had been searching for all these years and I could not go another day not having her as my wife. So, we joined our two families on March 19, in a state other than our own, where it's legal for us to be married. In Indiana, we are still fighting for same sex marriage rights and equality. I enjoy each and every day having the woman of my dreams in my arms and raising our two beautiful daughters together. Life is truly amazing!

On another note, thank you for having this page and always showing support to those in our community who don't get it from others. Many of the posts helped me feel more comfortable about my lifestyle change and with coming out.

Find your happiness, be who you are, fight for it, do whatever you have to do, because it's never too late to live Happily Ever After!

Jenn

This is our story, me (on the left) and my partner (on the right) met each other 5 years ago, we were the best of friends, but we soon realised that we were destined to be more. We are both only 16 but have been in a long term relationship for almost 2 years, we have gone through so much crap to get to where we are today, there were times when we couldn't even speak because we were only 15 and still under the control of our parents, who were not completely supportive of the relationship which made it was really hard to keep the relationship going but there was no way at all we were giving up because our love for each other was too strong, but at 16 we finally got past all of that, and we are now officially engaged and living together. There's been many ups and many downs in the past few years but Kayleigh was worth it in the end... I am also called Kayleigh (just to confuse you) but this shows that no matter what age you are, or gender you are, love can happen, it is possible, and the right one can come along. I just wanted to share a brief story.
Share this info so that pride would never disappear

In about three months I get to marry my best friend. I never thought we would see the law pass in this lifetime. I never expected to get to call her my wife, marriage wasn't even an option for "people like us.' But I would of loved you just the same. 

They say if you dream hard enough, those dreams can come true. Mine came true the day I layed eyes on you. It turns out my prince charming was a princess. 

Some people say were too young to get married, too young to know, that soul mates don't exist. But I don't believe them. They will never know how close we have come from the same-sex struggles that we face on a daily basis. Society hasn't stopped us yet and they never will, they just made us stronger.

I promise I will love you forever. I will be there to hold your hand through the darkness and be your guiding light, to care for you when your too old weak to walk, to make you protein brownies when you crave them, and to call you my wife until I leave this god forsaken earth. I love you

Four gay men allow us into their intimate world of fatherhood.
Fatherhood Dreams invites people into the day-to-day lives of gay dads Scott, Steve, Randy and Drew, who are fathers through ADOPTION, CO-PARENTING and SURROGACY. We'll stay with Steve and his co-parenting partners, lesbian mothers Coreen and Wendy while they are raising two children on an isolated island. We'll hear from a surrogate mother expecting Scott's twins. And we'll visit the house of adopted child's birth family that chose Randy and Drew, a gay family, to be the parents to baby Jack.

These men represent a new possibility, showing how in a modern world gay parenting can transform from a distant dream into a reality.

From our inbox:

Dear LGBT News,

At a early age, I knew I was a girl and not a boy. Puberty, I had grown breasts. So I knew I was mostly born in the wrong body. Just the down stairs doesn't fit me at all. Hiding them wasn't easy. I couldn't wear what I wanted to wear, because I know my parents are like those are for girls. In my head I was like "Yes I am." Being in the south doesn't help much. I got made fun of because of my breasts. Even though I was cross dressing alone in my room to make me feel like myself. On one day of high school. I was wearing my tight girly jeans. I had gotten compliments from the girls saying I looked good in them and just angry eyes from guys. After that day I never wore them to school again. When I got out of high school that I started to let my hair grow out. Which is a good thing. Now, I have only come out to one of my friends recently and she supports me very well. Yet, I don't know how my family would react to such news. I have such a fear of being disowned by them. I asked my friend of how he felt if one of his friends was a transsexual. All he said was "I don't care." Even though the friend I came out to was sitting next to me. It just didn't come out. Although I am planning to come out to the family that not only I am Bi, but also a transsexual woman. I plan to do it on my birthday which is a little ways away. The fear of it still lingers in me. My mom supports those that are LGBT. I just don't know if she would react differently if it were her son. She also the one that thinks the breasts are a condition that men have. I certainly think not. So, I have to plan on how to come out. I am so scared, nervous, and anxious to hear what all of them have to say. I hope it goes well.

Sincerely, Haley

This is the story I have been telling my 10yr old daughter how Mommy and I met since she was 4yrs old ... 
" AT THE END OF THE RAINBOW" 
It all started with me being a kid always wanting to know anything and everything... When I was about 4yrs. old I saw these beautiful color's in the sky and asked my mommy, "what was that?" She said, its a rainbow mamas and I said, "A rainbow? WOW IT'S SO BEAUTIFUL!!!" She smiled and said, "yes My Love a rainbow" ... Five years go by, and I was playing outside as it started to rain and the sun was breaking through and there again my mom called me inside as we both saw the rainbow,this time I knew what it was and said, "Mommy look, isn't it beautiful!!!? " she smiled and said "yes baby come inside " 
I asked her, "Mommy what's at the beginning and end of the rainbow ? " 
she replied, " when u were born is the beginning and at the end is the pot of gold Mamas... " I said, "wow mommy someday I want to find the pot of gold ..." She smiled and said, "I will pray that u do mamas and when u do I can die happy"... We both smiled and then 8 more years go by and I am graduating high school right after I walk there is a rainbow and my mother cries and holds me tight and we smile and I say, "Mom I am only going to collage I will be back in the summer and visit u every holiday I will be fine ..." My mother said, "Baby I know" and we looked at the rainbow together like it was our last time together then we went home and I packed, she said her good byes and told me," it is time to find your pot of gold" I laughed and said, "mom you are silly I am no longer a kid I know there is no gold at the end of the rainbow " she winked and smiled and I left... At 23 years old I did so much in life and finished school and had a job and thought," now what is next? "There is something missing ...? This long journey over this big big mountain of life I felt I was not done and empty then I meet this Beautiful woman whom bumps into me as the sun is blinding her eyes from seeing where she was going she apologizes and we lock eyes feeling so much emotions in my heart I look to the sky and see almost a full rainbow she looked up and notices it as well and we look and smile at one another then there I see this Beautiful Lil 3yr old girl holding her hand and she says, "this is my daughter Kammy and I am Chelly" I smiled with butterflies in my tummy and said, "my name is Becky it is very nice to meet you..." We talked for so long and Chelly looked at her watch and said she had to go back home to her leprechaun Armando whom she is no longer with anymore but she had to go back to him because she had no where else to go for they had shared her... So i think to myself she is staying with him still so I said "ok well it's nice meeting a new friend " and she said with her beautiful smile yes that it is... "and walked away we talked for a few months and she confessed her love to me as I confessed mine. So I asked her to move in with me in my Castle, her and Kammy, she said ok and we became a family later that year my mother wanted to visit and meet the two loves of my life so we made a dinner date with her and she came over we talked and laughed and played games she fell in love with both my girls and understood why my love was so real and true for Chelly and Kammy as Chelly put Kammy to sleep my mom and I walked outside there was a bright light and sprinklers went on and we saw a very light rainbow my mother said "oh Becky look" and I said, "I know mom it's a rainbow they are so beautiful" 
She told me about how my dream was when I was Little, how i wanted to find the pot of gold and I laughed and said "yeah I was a crazy kid wasn't I mom ?" She looked at me and said with tears of joy, "No my baby girl finally after 23 years you found your pot of gold" as She looked at Chelly walking outside to where we were and i said , "Why Mom you are so right I never understood you telling me about the Pot of gold till now..." we both winked and smiled as I held Chelly close To my heart, my mom said, " now I can die Happy...." So Becky, Chelly and Kammy lived far from the leprechaun man and Happily Ever After with new Beginnings...

From our inbox:

You guys always post things about families who have disowned or said terrible things to their gay/lesbian children and so I think it's time for a happy one! My name is Katie and I'm from smack dab in the middle of the Bible Belt! Just where you think hate would be at its worst.. But my family isn't another statistic. When I was 14 I sat my mom down and told her I liked girls; I was crying my eyes out and begging her to help me change. She laughed at me and told me that she already knew I was gay because a mother knows her child. She never treated me any different and when my dad found out he said he was relieved because I wouldn't make him a grandpa on accident!  after several crash-and-burn type relationships I found this lovely lady. She supports all of my dreams and pushes me to be a better person. Two years and a lot of hardships later, we are a happy little family. I know if my mom were still alive she would love my girlfriend like her own child and I know my dad sure does! Coming out isn't always as bad as you think. You might just have a family like mine!

Story of our perfect family:
Not in my wildest deems would I have ever thought I would be where I am today,
I (top right) met my fiancée kayleigh 6 1/2 years ago, and even then it was unimaginable!
Years on we have two beautiful girls, 5 and 2 whom we created together with upmost love and the promise of a happy safe and secure family life.
Our eldest is always being complimented on how proud she is of her family and how she will tell anyone who listens.
Now the harsh part. We cannot legally marry and will not conform to what WE feel a patronising way of shutting the gay community up by "letting" us have civil partnership.
This is a major sacrifice we have had to make due to the fact that for some reason kayleigh cannot be named on OUR daughters birth certificates unless we are civil partnered. Baring in mind that straight couples who for whatever reason have a child that is not biologically from both parents are still allowed on the birth certificate, despite whether they have made a commitment to each other through marriage (which I thought was supposed to be a legal bond between the couple) or not!
But we are happy. I changed my surname through deed-poll so that we are all united in that way at-least!
I love my girls and fiancee and we won't let anyone make us feel any less than a beautifully lovingly home made family :0)


June 3Sophie Pleb George

For Lanie from Chetta with love from our inbox:
Hi, 
My name is Chetta and I've been seeing all the stories that y'all share on here, I was wondering if maybe you can share mine. 
You see there was a point in time where I was so broken. I felt so alone in this big big world. I've known Lanie for 10 years but we lost touch over time, I found her on Facebook and we started catching up on everything. It didn't take long for me to notice how bright my days had become when we talked. I would get a text and before I even read it I was smiling from ear to ear. Needless to say we decided to give it a go. I was nervous about giving my broken heart to another person, afraid that it would be broken more. I won't lie and say things have been perfect, everyone has obstacles to overcome. Although we've had rocky times I will never regret one minute of it. I can truly say I'm in love with my best friend. She's all a girl could ask for and I wouldn't trade her for anything in the world. 
For the people out there struggling just remember... The odds may be against you but Never give up on love and when you love love hard! 

THIS IS FOR YOU MY BABY LANIE NICOLE BOURGEOIS YOU ARE MY HEART AND SOUL AND IM LOOKING FORWARD TO SPENDING THE REST OF MY LIFE BY YOUR SIDE! 
FOREVER THINE. FOREVER MINE. FOREVER OURS.

This is a breathtaking story!
I became a mother, and I placed my son up for adoption. This choice gives me no sadness, only joy, because I have blessed two people's lives with the chance to be parents. The couple I chose for my son happens to be gay.

The moment they saw Ian, they both burst in to tears.
"Would you like to hold him?" I asked. (He was born premature, with clefts in his brain, so he remained in Infant Special Care until he was four weeks, hence our lovely yellow gowns.)
Both John and Doug couldn't stop staring at him, thanking me, telling me how gorgeous he was.

I spent my nights in the hospital holding Ian and staring at him, completely in wonder at how much he looked like his dad, and trying to decide what the right decision for him was. I had never felt so much love for something in my entire life.
In my heart, I knew I was not yet a parent—I hardly know who I am as person—and after hours of silent tears and rocking him back and forth in my arms, I made the choice to give him the family that he deserves, and one that is capable to, not only take care of him, but give him opportunities I could not, even if I had all of the money in the world. 

Some will criticize my choice to place my son with a gay couple, but I believe they not only deserve the chance to be parents, but that they will be two of the best parents in the entire universe.

John and Doug email me weekly, with pictures and medical updates. I am allowed to visit any chance I can get (we, unfortunately, are 2000 miles apart), and they have completely made me a part of their family. My son will always know I am his mother, his mhibu (a word loosely translating to "dear one" in Swahili).

When people hear my story, the first thing they tell me is how "strong" I am, and how "hard" it must have been. My reply will always be the same:
I am just a mother who loves her son very, very much.
